# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-front-door
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:azure-front-door/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] An **application delivery network** (**ADN**) is a suite of technologies that, when deployed together, provide availability, security, visibility, and acceleration for Internet applications such as websites.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] ADN components provide supporting functionality that enables website content to be delivered to visitors and other users of that website, in a fast, secure, and reliable way.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Gartner defines application delivery networking as the combination of WAN optimization controllers (WOCs) and application delivery controllers (ADCs).
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In the branch office portion of an ADN is the WAN optimization controller, which works to reduce the number of bits that flow over the network using caching and compression, and shapes TCP traffic using prioritization and other optimization techniques.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Some WOC components are installed on PCs or mobile clients, and there is typically a portion of the WOC installed in the data center.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Application delivery networks are also offered by some CDN vendors.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] An Application Delivery Network (ADN) enhances the delivery of applications across the Internet by employing a number of optimization techniques.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In theory, an Application Delivery Network (ADN) is closely related to a content delivery network.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The difference between the two delivery networks lies in the intelligence of the ADN to understand and optimize applications, usually referred to as application fluency.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Application Fluent Network (AFN) is based on the concept of Application Fluency to refer to WAN optimization techniques applied at Layer Four to Layer Seven of the OSI model for networks.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Application Fluency implies that the network is fluent or intelligent in understanding and being able to optimize delivery of each application.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Application Fluent Network is an addition of SDN capabilities.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The acronym 'AFN' is used by Alcatel-Lucent Enterprise to refer to an Application Fluent Network.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Application delivery uses one or more layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch to intelligently distribute traffic to a pool, also known as a cluster or farm, of servers.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The application delivery controller (ADC) is assigned a single virtual IP address (VIP) that represents the pool of servers.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the ADC is then directed to one of the servers in the pool (cluster, farm) based on a number of factors including application specific data values, application transport protocol, availability of servers, current performance metrics, and client-specific parameters.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] An ADN provides the advantages of load distribution, increase in capacity of servers, improved scalability, security, and increased reliability through application specific health checks.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Increasingly the ADN comprises a redundant pair of ADC on which is integrated a number of different feature sets designed to provide security, availability, reliability, and acceleration functions.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In some cases these devices are still separate entities, deployed together as a network of devices through which application traffic is delivered, each providing specific functionality that enhances the delivery of the application.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] TCP Multiplexing is loosely based on established connection pooling techniques utilized by application server platforms to optimize the execution of database queries from within applications.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] An ADC establishes a number of connections to the servers in its pool and keeps the connections open.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] When a request is received by the ADC from the client, the request is evaluated and then directed to a server over an existing connection.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This has the effect of reducing the overhead imposed by establishing and tearing down the TCP connection with the server, improving the responsiveness of the application.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Some ADN implementations take this technique one step further and also multiplex HTTP and application requests.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This has the benefit of executing requests in parallel, which enhances the performance of the application.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] There are a number of Request for Comments (RFCs) which describe mechanisms for improving the performance of TCP.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Many ADN implement these RFCs in order to provide enhanced delivery of applications through more efficient use of TCP.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] ADNs also provide optimization of application data through caching and compression techniques.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] There are two types of compression used by ADNs today: industry standard HTTP compression and proprietary data reduction algorithms.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] It is important to note that the cost in CPU cycles to compress data when traversing a LAN can result in a negative performance impact and therefore best practices are to only utilize compression when delivering applications via a WAN or particularly congested high-speed data link.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] HTTP compression is asymmetric and transparent to the client.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Support for HTTP compression is built into web servers and web browsers.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] All commercial ADN products currently support HTTP compression.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] A second compression technique is achieved through data reduction algorithms.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Because these algorithms are proprietary and modify the application traffic, they are symmetric and require a device to reassemble the application traffic before the client can receive it.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Advanced health checking is the ability of an ADN to determine not only the state of the server on which an application is hosted, but the status of the application it is delivering.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Advanced health checking techniques allow the ADC to intelligently determine whether or not the content being returned by the server is correct and should be delivered to the client.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This feature enables other reliability features in the ADN, such as resending a request to a different server if the content returned by the original server is found to be erroneous.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The load balancing algorithms found in today's ADN are far more advanced than the simplistic round-robin and least connections algorithms used in the early 1990s.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] These algorithms were originally loosely based on operating systems' scheduling algorithms, but have since evolved to factor in conditions peculiar to networking and application environments.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] It is more accurate to describe today's "load balancing" algorithms as application routing algorithms, as most ADN employ application awareness to determine whether an application is available to respond to a request.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This includes the ability of the ADN to determine not only whether the application is available, but whether or not the application can respond to the request within specified parameters, often referred to as a service level agreement.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The ADN provides fault tolerance at the server level, within pools or farms.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This is accomplished by designating specific servers as a 'backup' that is activated automatically by the ADN in the event that the primary server(s) in the pool fail.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The ADN also ensures application availability and reliability through its ability to seamlessly "failover" to a secondary device in the event of a hardware or software failure.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This ensures that traffic continues to flow in the event of a failure in one device, thereby providing fault tolerance for the applications.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Fault tolerance is implemented in ADNs through either a network or serial based connection.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The Virtual IP Address (VIP) is shared between two devices.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] A heartbeat daemon on the secondary device verifies that the primary device is active.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In the event that the heartbeat is lost, the secondary device assumes the shared VIP and begins servicing requests.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This process is not immediate, and though most ADN replicate sessions from the primary to the secondary, there is no way to guarantee that sessions initiated during the time it takes for the secondary to assume the VIP and begin managing traffic will be maintained.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In a serial connection based failover configuration two ADN devices communicate via a standard RS-232 connection instead of the network, and all sharing of session information and status is exchanged over this connection.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Failover is nearly instantaneous, though it suffers from the same constraints regarding sessions initiated while the primary device is failing as network based failover.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Although often erroneously assigned to the application layer, SSL is the most common method of securing application traffic through an ADN today.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] SSL uses PKI to establish a secure connection between the client and the ADN, making it difficult for attackers to decrypt the data in transit or hijack the session.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The use of a virtual IP address (VIP) and position of the ADN in the network provides the means through which certain resources can be cloaked, or hidden, from the client.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Because the ADN is designed to understand applications and application protocols, such as HTTP, it can manipulate certain aspects of the protocol to cloak the servers in the pool and prevent potentially useful information regarding the software and hardware infrastructure from being exposed.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] A typical use of this functionality is to hide the operating system and server software used to host the application.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This is usually accomplished by rewriting the Server field in an HTTP response.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] A second typical use of this functionality is the exploitation of the ADN's ability to rewrite the URI portion of an HTTP request.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The client is presented with a URI and VIP that are known only to the ADN, and upon receiving the request the ADN may either (a) rewrite the URI and send a 302 redirect or (b) transparently translates the URI and responds to the client as if the URI were the right one in the first place.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In recent years commercial ADNs have begun to include application firewall functionality to further secure applications during the delivery process.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Many commercial ADN companies have acquired and integrated these functions and present such features as part of a defense in depth strategy often cited by security professionals.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The ADN is most often deployed in the DMZ at the edge of the network.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] This results in exposure to potential network layer attacks including Denial of Service (DoS) from ICMP and SYN floods.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] As a result, the ADN must necessarily protect not only itself but the applications it is delivering from succumbing to such attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The ADN generally employs a number of protections against typical network layer attacks though it does not implement the full security offered by an IPS.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Delayed binding, also called TCP splicing, is the postponement of the connection between the client and the server in order to obtain sufficient information to make a routing decision.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] Some application switches and routers delay binding the client session to the server until the proper handshakes are complete so as to prevent Denial of Service attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] ADNs often have the ability to filter traffic based on Access Control Lists (ACLs), Bogus IP ranges (Bogon filtering) and deep packet inspection pattern matching.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] In some cases, thresholds or rate limiting of IP addresses or ranges of IP addresses may be employed.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] ADNs are increasingly adding advanced traffic management functionality.
[src:azure-front-door/application-delivery-network] The deep packet inspection capabilities of some of these products can identify traffic by application type and can be used to analyze, block, shape and prioritize traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:azure-front-door/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:azure-front-door/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:azure-front-door/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:azure-front-door/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
